My makefiles are completely portable across all my Unix and OS/2 boxes.  All 
I ever change is the compiler flags line :)  I have found unix makefiles 
written by people who make (incorrect) assumptions about your setup, and 
they cannot be run on OTHER unix systems....  You have to hack them for an 
hour or 2 to make them work (cbzone, xtank, kermit though it is better than 
before).  I cant help it if the people writing the makefiles dont really 
know how to write portable ones (as they use all the nice little shortcuts 
they are used to, which are completely non-portable.... :( )

However, for my OS/2 work, I have found my makefiles port with a single line 
change, that being the compiler flags....

With HPFS I have my nice little UNIX directory structure complete with long 
file names.  

Finally, when i get something I want to port to OS/2, I take the UNIX 
makefile, hack at it a bit (adjust compiler, flags, etc) and voila it 
works...

